The March 11, 2011, Mw = 9.1 Tohoku (Japan) earthquake is one of the largest earthquakes of the instrumental era and is to date the best recorded megathrust event.

This event has been used as a test case for an end-to-end execution of the PTF workflow global version, including on-the-fly tsunami simulations.

The original PTF code is available from the DT-GEO workflow registry (https://gitlab.com/dtgeo/workflow-management-system/workflow-registry/-/tree/main/DTC61/WF6101?ref_type=heads). For the sake of simplicity and conciseness, the codes in this notebook (as well in the external functions.ipynb notebook) have been revised and some general options have been removed, to focus on the specific site demonstrator.

Moreover, Step 4 is not provided here since the conversion of the hazard into Alert Levels is a prerogative of the TSP (Tsunami Service Providers).

To execute the notebook a Python environment including all the required modules must be activated. Anyway, an already executed html version of the notebook is also provided.

print('Creating discretized ensemble')
ensemble = dict()

# discretized magnitude
ensemble['magnitude'], ensemble['magnitude_idx'] = select_magnitude(event_dict, magnitude_values, sigma)
                                                          
# discretized positions in geographic coordinates
location_ellipse_2d = build_location_ellipsoid_objects(event           = event_dict,
                                                       sigma           = sigma,
                                                       seismicity_type = 'BS')

position_step = 25000.
utm_x, utm_y = discretized_position(location_ellipse_2d, position_step)

ensemble['position_utm_x'] = utm_x
ensemble['position_utm_y'] = utm_y

# discretized depth in km
tmp = load_lambda_BSPS(sigma, event_dict)

ellipsoid_3d = tmp['gaussian_ellipsoid']

depth_step = 5000.
ensemble['depth'] = discretized_depth(-ellipsoid_3d['zp'], depth_step)

grid_3d, lon, lat = create_grid3d(event_dict, ensemble)

# fix for negative longitudes
lon[lon<0] += 360.
                    
ensemble['grid_3d'] = grid_3d
ensemble['position_geo_lon'] = lon
ensemble['position_geo_lat'] = lat

# focal mechanism for Tohoku 2011 from USGS (https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eventpage/official20110311054624120_30/moment-tensor)
focal_mechanism = {'np1': {'strike': 193.0, 'dip': 9.0, 'rake': 78.0},
                   'np2': {'strike': 25.0, 'dip': 81.0, 'rake': 92.0}}

strike_step = 15.0
strike_sigma = 15.0
dip_step = 8.0

rake_step = 15.0
rake_sigma = 15.0

ensemble['focal_mechanism'] = discretized_mechanism(focal_mechanism, strike_step, strike_sigma, dip_step, dip_sigma,
                                                    rake_step, rake_sigma)         

ensemble['fault_size'] = compute_fault_size(ensemble['magnitude'])

ensemble['slip'] = compute_slip(ensemble['magnitude'], ensemble['fault_size'], rigidity)

In[39]:
hc_pois = hc_pois_sbs

list_percentiles = [50, 15, 10, 5, 1]
percentiles = np.array(list_percentiles) * 0.01
n_percentiles = len(percentiles)
mih_percentiles = np.zeros((n_pois, n_percentiles)) 

for i in range(n_pois):
    mih_percentiles[i,:] = np.interp(percentiles, hc_pois[i,::-1], thresholds[::-1])

hc_d = dict()
hc_d['mean'] = scipy.integrate.simpson(hc_pois, thresholds)

# percentiles' labels are expressed as 1-p since they represent the survival function (not exceedance)
for ip, percentile in enumerate(percentiles):
    if percentile == 0:
        print('Percentile 100 is not allowed.')
    elif percentile != 0.0001:
        hc_d['p' +  '{:.0f}'.format((1-percentile)*100).zfill(2)] = mih_percentiles[:,ip]
    else:
        hc_d['envelope'] = mih_percentiles[:,ip]
